etymologies: mid 17th century (in the sense ‘a person who inducts or initiates’): from late Latin, from Latin inducere (see induce), or from induct+ -or. Current senses date from the early 20th century

definitions: a component in an electric or electronic circuit which possesses inductance.
shortDefinitions: component in electric or electronic circuit which possesses inductance

definitions: a substance that promotes an equilibrium reaction by reacting with one of the substances produced.
shortDefinitions: substance that promotes equilibrium reaction by reacting with one of substances produced
